title: 1861-A
statement: A. For example, $$$2$$$, $$$3$$$, $$$13$$$ and $$$101$$$ are prime numbers; $$$1$$$, $$$4$$$, $$$6$$$ and $$$42$$$ are not.You are given a sequence of digits from $$$1$$$ to $$$9$$$, in whichevery digit from $$$1$$$ to $$$9$$$ appears exactly once.You are allowed to do the following operationseveral (maybe zero) times: choose any digit from the sequence and delete it.However, you cannot perform this operation if the sequence consists of only two digits.Your goal is to obtain a sequence which represents a prime number. You are given a sequence of the digits from 1 to 9, where each digit appears exactly once. You can repeatedly remove one digit from the sequence, but you cannot remove digits if there are only two digits left.  

Your goal is to remove digits from the sequence to create a sequence that represents a prime number. A prime number is a whole number greater than 1 that has only two divisors: 1 and itself.

For each test case, print the resulting prime number sequence, or print -1 if it is impossible to create a prime number by removing digits.

You are given a list of the digits 1 through 9, each appearing only once. You can remove one digit at a time from the list.  Your goal is to remove digits until the remaining digits form a prime number. If this is impossible, say so.
